WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.500 --> 00:00:02.890
JORDAN THIBODEAU: I'd like
to introduce Gino Blefari.

00:00:02.890 --> 00:00:05.250
Gino Blefari is a
chief executive officer

00:00:05.250 --> 00:00:08.296
for HSF Affiliates, which
operates the real estate

00:00:08.296 --> 00:00:10.170
brokerage network for
Berkshire Hathaway Home

00:00:10.170 --> 00:00:13.150
Services, Prudential Real
Estate and Real Living Real

00:00:13.150 --> 00:00:16.620
Estate, Warren Buffett's real
estate franchise business.

00:00:16.620 --> 00:00:19.290
Blefari has an award-winning
agent, manager,

00:00:19.290 --> 00:00:20.580
and broker owner.

00:00:20.580 --> 00:00:23.730
He came to his position
at HSF Affiliates

00:00:23.730 --> 00:00:27.440
from Silicon Valley, CA-based
Intero Real Estate Services,

00:00:27.440 --> 00:00:32.110
Inc., which he founded in 2002
and through mid-2014 served

00:00:32.110 --> 00:00:34.480
as its president and CEO.

00:00:34.480 --> 00:00:36.650
Under Blefari's
direction, Intero

00:00:36.650 --> 00:00:39.460
became one of the fastest,
organically growing companies

00:00:39.460 --> 00:00:41.090
in the history of real estate.

00:00:41.090 --> 00:00:44.790
In 2014, Intero ranked seventh
nationwide for real estate

00:00:44.790 --> 00:00:49.280
sales volume, according
to REAL Trends.

00:00:49.280 --> 00:00:52.200
Some of his recognition
includes ranked

00:00:52.200 --> 00:00:55.450
among top 25 most powerful
and influential leaders

00:00:55.450 --> 00:00:57.210
in the residential
real estate industry,

00:00:57.210 --> 00:01:02.140
according to the 2016
Swanepoel Power 200 rankings

00:01:02.140 --> 00:01:04.760
and 2007 Italian
Businessman of the Year

00:01:04.760 --> 00:01:07.450
by Italian American
Heritage Foundation.

00:01:07.450 --> 00:01:10.280
And last but not least, he
was my real estate professor

00:01:10.280 --> 00:01:12.210
at De Anza Community College.

00:01:12.210 --> 00:01:14.120
So let's give Gino a
warm welcome to Google.

00:01:14.120 --> 00:01:14.760
GINO BLEFARI: Thanks.

00:01:14.760 --> 00:01:15.926
JORDAN THIBODEAU: Thank you.

00:01:15.926 --> 00:01:17.415
[APPLAUSE]

00:01:20.310 --> 00:01:25.377
So for the first question, I
was going to start off with,

00:01:25.377 --> 00:01:27.210
can you talk about the
different real estate

00:01:27.210 --> 00:01:28.227
investments you've made?

00:01:28.227 --> 00:01:29.810
GINO BLEFARI: My
personal investments?

00:01:29.810 --> 00:01:30.870
JORDAN THIBODEAU: Yeah,
your personal investments.

00:01:30.870 --> 00:01:31.125
GINO BLEFARI: Sure.

00:01:31.125 --> 00:01:33.333
JORDAN THIBODEAU: And what
has been one of your best?

00:01:33.333 --> 00:01:34.450
GINO BLEFARI: OK.

00:01:34.450 --> 00:01:37.290
You know, I'm not a huge
real estate investor,

00:01:37.290 --> 00:01:39.040
but being in the
real estate business,

00:01:39.040 --> 00:01:41.340
I remember when I
started in there I

00:01:41.340 --> 00:01:43.850
had heard from some trainer
that it would be great to try

00:01:43.850 --> 00:01:46.030
to buy one house every year.

00:01:46.030 --> 00:01:49.101
And so the first probably seven
years of my career, that's

00:01:49.101 --> 00:01:49.600
what I did.

00:01:49.600 --> 00:01:50.370
I bought a house.

00:01:50.370 --> 00:01:52.260
And I had a rule then.

00:01:52.260 --> 00:01:54.530
The rule there
was I wanted to be

00:01:54.530 --> 00:01:56.720
able to drive to
it within one hour.

00:01:56.720 --> 00:02:00.350
So that was my
simple rule there.

00:02:00.350 --> 00:02:05.610
In turn, traded those seven
houses into a building,

00:02:05.610 --> 00:02:08.500
and what has turned out
as my best real estate

00:02:08.500 --> 00:02:13.310
investments over time have
been commercial buildings.

00:02:13.310 --> 00:02:15.290
And I'll give you
a case in point.

00:02:15.290 --> 00:02:19.560
If you look at the Intero
building on Santa Cruz Avenue

00:02:19.560 --> 00:02:22.550
there, that was some of
my little rental houses

00:02:22.550 --> 00:02:23.689
that I rolled into that.

00:02:23.689 --> 00:02:25.230
I actually built
that building there.

00:02:25.230 --> 00:02:27.800
It turned out to
be a great return.

00:02:27.800 --> 00:02:32.280
And a funny story of how
investments, sometimes you

00:02:32.280 --> 00:02:35.520
think they're good, and then
you think they're terrible.

00:02:35.520 --> 00:02:38.690
And then they turn out to
be good, back and forth.

00:02:38.690 --> 00:02:45.200
In 2005, I bought
a piece of dirt

00:02:45.200 --> 00:02:49.370
on El Camino Real right
here in Menlo Park.

00:02:49.370 --> 00:02:50.970
It was an old gas station.

00:02:50.970 --> 00:02:53.130
And it had already
been cleaned up.

00:02:53.130 --> 00:02:55.690
And I was going to
build a building.

00:02:55.690 --> 00:02:57.666
And at the time,
2005, as you remember,

00:02:57.666 --> 00:02:59.290
the real estate market
was really good.

00:02:59.290 --> 00:03:01.132
So Intero was doing terrific.

00:03:01.132 --> 00:03:03.090
I thought, OK, I'm going
to build this building

00:03:03.090 --> 00:03:06.080
and open up a real estate
office in Menlo Park.

00:03:06.080 --> 00:03:09.830
So I had hassles with the city,
and hassles with the city,

00:03:09.830 --> 00:03:11.070
hassles with the city.

00:03:11.070 --> 00:03:14.790
And they didn't finish
the building until 2008.

00:03:14.790 --> 00:03:18.390
Well, 2008 was right in
the brink of this recession

00:03:18.390 --> 00:03:19.790
that we have, right?

00:03:19.790 --> 00:03:21.210
And so it was a terrible time.

00:03:21.210 --> 00:03:23.334
So there was no way I could
put an Intero in there.

00:03:23.334 --> 00:03:26.360
So I had this building
that I had debt on.

00:03:26.360 --> 00:03:31.430
And I'm not some
multi-millionaire investor

00:03:31.430 --> 00:03:33.220
at that time at all.

00:03:33.220 --> 00:03:36.840
And so I had debt on it that
was costing me about $48,000

00:03:36.840 --> 00:03:37.730
a month.

00:03:37.730 --> 00:03:39.020
And it was vacant.

00:03:39.020 --> 00:03:41.940
It's not a very good investment.

00:03:41.940 --> 00:03:44.160
I think everybody in
the room would agree.

00:03:44.160 --> 00:03:47.220
But I was lucky enough to get
Stanford Medical to lease it.

00:03:47.220 --> 00:03:51.630
So I had Stanford Medical in it
and Pendleton in a little 2,500

00:03:51.630 --> 00:03:52.450
square feet.

00:03:52.450 --> 00:03:55.620
And they leased it for like,
maybe, 55 grand a month.

00:03:55.620 --> 00:03:57.380
So I had a tiny
bit of a cash flow,

00:03:57.380 --> 00:04:00.520
but I never pulled
one penny out of it.

00:04:00.520 --> 00:04:05.140
And I think about a
year ago right now,

00:04:05.140 --> 00:04:08.520
because rates were so low,
I refinanced the building.

00:04:08.520 --> 00:04:11.450
And they appraised it
when you refinance,

00:04:11.450 --> 00:04:15.540
and they appraised it for
$10 million, which was fine.

00:04:15.540 --> 00:04:17.496
I think I owed about
$5 million on it.

00:04:17.496 --> 00:04:18.870
But I'm going to
keep it, haven't

00:04:18.870 --> 00:04:21.180
taken a penny out
of it, zero return,

00:04:21.180 --> 00:04:24.470
just whatever appreciation
you might have.

00:04:24.470 --> 00:04:26.350
And I got a call from
the commercial broker

00:04:26.350 --> 00:04:29.740
that leased it, a guy from
Cornish &amp; Carey Commercial.

00:04:29.740 --> 00:04:32.390
He says, hey, you want to sell
your building in Menlo Park?

00:04:32.390 --> 00:04:34.270
Naw, I just refinanced it.

00:04:34.270 --> 00:04:36.110
You know, this is
a long-term hold.

00:04:36.110 --> 00:04:37.940
It almost broke me.

00:04:37.940 --> 00:04:40.370
But he goes, well, I got
a stupid offer for you.

00:04:40.370 --> 00:04:41.000
I go, really?

00:04:41.000 --> 00:04:41.510
How much?

00:04:41.510 --> 00:04:44.862
He goes well, $13,100,000.

00:04:44.862 --> 00:04:49.010
Oh, well, go ahead and
send me a letter of LOI.

00:04:49.010 --> 00:04:50.740
So he sent me a letter of LOI.

00:04:50.740 --> 00:04:55.790
And I had one of the Intero
agents, commercial agent,

00:04:55.790 --> 00:04:58.790
lease the downstairs
2,500 square feet.

00:04:58.790 --> 00:05:00.410
And I had them lease that.

00:05:00.410 --> 00:05:01.993
And so I called him
up, said, hey, I'm

00:05:01.993 --> 00:05:03.940
going to need a
copy of the contract

00:05:03.940 --> 00:05:06.580
because I might be
selling the building.

00:05:06.580 --> 00:05:08.480
He says, oh, what's going on?

00:05:08.480 --> 00:05:10.240
So I tell him what's going on.

00:05:10.240 --> 00:05:12.780
That Monday, the
following Monday,

00:05:12.780 --> 00:05:15.832
I got an offer on the building
that was worth $10 million

00:05:15.832 --> 00:05:20.260
for $15 million all cash with
like a 30-day close, right?

00:05:20.260 --> 00:05:23.570
So what turned out
to be one of those,

00:05:23.570 --> 00:05:26.460
Travis said, crazy,
like, oh my gosh.

00:05:26.460 --> 00:05:27.710
How did I get into this?

00:05:27.710 --> 00:05:30.320
Now, I'm always the majority
owner in the buildings,

00:05:30.320 --> 00:05:33.860
and I drag a bunch of my
friends in with little pieces

00:05:33.860 --> 00:05:34.680
of the whole thing.

00:05:34.680 --> 00:05:36.304
And so it turned out
to be a good deal.

00:05:36.304 --> 00:05:41.520
But that might be one of the
more successful-- definitely

00:05:41.520 --> 00:05:47.330
is the most successful
deal that I did there.

00:05:47.330 --> 00:05:50.629
Also, when we're speaking
about real estate investments,

00:05:50.629 --> 00:05:52.170
coming out of that
investment, then I

00:05:52.170 --> 00:05:54.880
had several million dollars
that I needed to roll over

00:05:54.880 --> 00:05:56.030
into other properties.

00:05:56.030 --> 00:06:00.200
And with my new job as the
CEO of HSF Affiliates--

00:06:00.200 --> 00:06:02.020
and we operate
Berkshire Hathaway Home

00:06:02.020 --> 00:06:05.110
Services that brand and
Prudential and Real Living--

00:06:05.110 --> 00:06:08.360
I'm constantly on the road and
visiting affiliates, you know,

00:06:08.360 --> 00:06:09.720
franchisees.

00:06:09.720 --> 00:06:11.890
And so I'm in Chattanooga,
Tennessee, and you know,

00:06:11.890 --> 00:06:15.060
I tell them, so, do you have
any good deals out here?

00:06:15.060 --> 00:06:17.250
We're always looking
for good deals.

00:06:17.250 --> 00:06:19.090
Funny thing, in
Chattanooga, Tennessee,

00:06:19.090 --> 00:06:22.500
I was able to buy
five single family

00:06:22.500 --> 00:06:26.420
homes for like $110,000 each.

00:06:26.420 --> 00:06:28.690
And they rented for $1,300.

00:06:28.690 --> 00:06:31.840
You don't find those kind
of deals like right here.

00:06:31.840 --> 00:06:38.590
So most of the investments
in real estate for now

00:06:38.590 --> 00:06:39.310
seem to be good.

00:06:39.310 --> 00:06:41.070
But look at that Menlo Park one.

00:06:41.070 --> 00:06:43.230
In 2008, it was terrible.

00:06:43.230 --> 00:06:44.230
JORDAN THIBODEAU: Right.

00:06:44.230 --> 00:06:46.810
Now, when you made a
decision to buy in Tennessee,

00:06:46.810 --> 00:06:49.100
what metrics were you
looking at to determine

00:06:49.100 --> 00:06:50.520
if it was a good investment?

00:06:50.520 --> 00:06:53.430
GINO BLEFARI: I was just
looking for a good return, not

00:06:53.430 --> 00:06:54.550
any specific number.

00:06:54.550 --> 00:06:57.230
But OK, I can buy
it for this price.

00:06:57.230 --> 00:06:59.850
And here's how much cash flow.

00:06:59.850 --> 00:07:01.777
I'm kind of all
about cash flow now.

00:07:01.777 --> 00:07:03.110
JORDAN THIBODEAU: Exactly, yeah.

00:07:03.110 --> 00:07:04.984
They have a rule of
thumb called the 1% rule.

00:07:04.984 --> 00:07:08.720
So by you bringing $1,300 a
month, buy it for $100,000.

00:07:08.720 --> 00:07:10.470
I mean, that exceeds 1%, so--

00:07:10.470 --> 00:07:11.970
GINO BLEFARI: Yeah,
it's pretty hard

00:07:11.970 --> 00:07:13.760
to do almost anywhere else.

00:07:13.760 --> 00:07:14.801
JORDAN THIBODEAU: Gotcha.

00:07:17.100 --> 00:07:19.250
GINO BLEFARI: I kind of
spread it out a little bit.

00:07:19.250 --> 00:07:22.840
Before my rule was it's
got to be one hour away.

00:07:22.840 --> 00:07:25.400
Now my rule is it's
got a cash flow.

00:07:25.400 --> 00:07:29.200
I'm lucky enough, though, to
know real estate professionals.

00:07:29.200 --> 00:07:33.240
Like Travis is here
in the audience right

00:07:33.240 --> 00:07:34.670
over here, Travis Conte.

00:07:34.670 --> 00:07:38.770
So I know people like
Travis all over the country.

00:07:38.770 --> 00:07:41.910
And so it's not me trying
to guess is this good.

00:07:41.910 --> 00:07:43.750
Because a lot of
times you can guess,

00:07:43.750 --> 00:07:46.240
but you don't have all the
details that you really

00:07:46.240 --> 00:07:47.480
need to know about it.

00:07:47.480 --> 00:07:49.480
And so I'm lucky enough
to have that all around.

00:07:53.240 --> 00:07:54.870
I've got a place
in Austin, Texas,

00:07:54.870 --> 00:07:58.650
because I knew Austin
was a pretty good market.

00:07:58.650 --> 00:08:02.405
Believe it or not, I've got
a Starbucks in Oklahoma.

00:08:02.405 --> 00:08:05.030
And if you Googled it-- I can't
even remember the city it's in,

00:08:05.030 --> 00:08:06.738
but if you Googled
it, it's where there's

00:08:06.738 --> 00:08:08.720
more tornadoes than anywhere.

00:08:08.720 --> 00:08:13.991
But the return was very, very
good, and I've got insurance.

00:08:13.991 --> 00:08:16.010
JORDAN THIBODEAU: Gotcha.

00:08:16.010 --> 00:08:18.360
What do you think
separates a good investor

00:08:18.360 --> 00:08:21.130
from a great investor
in real estate?

00:08:21.130 --> 00:08:22.050
GINO BLEFARI: Luck.

00:08:22.050 --> 00:08:23.722
[LAUGHTER]

00:08:24.870 --> 00:08:33.520
I mean, look, it's just like
with any type of investing.

00:08:33.520 --> 00:08:36.100
It's someone with a good
strategy and the strategy

00:08:36.100 --> 00:08:39.130
that fits for them.

00:08:39.130 --> 00:08:43.039
Luck does play a
bit of it, though.

00:08:43.039 --> 00:08:47.990
Perfect example, my parents
were from Massachusetts.

00:08:47.990 --> 00:08:51.500
I grew up in Sunnyvale,
working class family.

00:08:51.500 --> 00:08:57.930
They happened to buy a house in
Sunnyvale in 1960 for $18,750.

00:08:57.930 --> 00:08:59.840
Now, we are from
Massachusetts, where

00:08:59.840 --> 00:09:04.570
they had a house that was about
$20,000, worth about $20,000.

00:09:04.570 --> 00:09:06.160
I went back when I
was visiting, when

00:09:06.160 --> 00:09:08.520
I toured through Massachusetts.

00:09:08.520 --> 00:09:11.840
I wanted to go to my
mom and dad's house.

00:09:11.840 --> 00:09:15.930
Their house is still worth
$20,000 in Massachusetts.

00:09:15.930 --> 00:09:18.280
Their house here in
an area of Birdland

00:09:18.280 --> 00:09:20.970
right by where the
new Apple's coming in,

00:09:20.970 --> 00:09:25.190
is probably worth at least
a million and a half,

00:09:25.190 --> 00:09:27.030
maybe a million eight.

00:09:27.030 --> 00:09:31.730
So there is some-- from an
appreciation standpoint,

00:09:31.730 --> 00:09:32.447
some of it is.

00:09:32.447 --> 00:09:34.280
JORDAN THIBODEAU: A lot
of us here at Google

00:09:34.280 --> 00:09:36.690
are thinking about
investing out of state,

00:09:36.690 --> 00:09:39.430
and so we have to
use our networks

00:09:39.430 --> 00:09:42.710
and try to determine what
would be a good partner for us

00:09:42.710 --> 00:09:44.860
to work with, how to find
a good property manager,

00:09:44.860 --> 00:09:46.730
how to find a good agent.

00:09:46.730 --> 00:09:48.260
What are things
that you look for

00:09:48.260 --> 00:09:53.610
in a quality investor-oriented
real estate agent?

00:09:53.610 --> 00:09:56.150
GINO BLEFARI: You know,
someone that understands

00:09:56.150 --> 00:09:57.360
the real estate investment.

00:09:57.360 --> 00:10:03.540
And lots of realtors,
they just sell houses.

00:10:03.540 --> 00:10:06.240
But you may not need
that commercial agent,

00:10:06.240 --> 00:10:10.296
which is more of like-- if
you're buying a building

00:10:10.296 --> 00:10:11.170
and things like that.

00:10:11.170 --> 00:10:13.690
But you want someone that
understands the numbers,

00:10:13.690 --> 00:10:21.870
understands, you know, the
return, just someone like that.

00:10:21.870 --> 00:10:22.920
I can do it myself now.

00:10:22.920 --> 00:10:26.480
It's like, OK, what
can I get a place for?

00:10:26.480 --> 00:10:27.642
What can it rent for?

00:10:27.642 --> 00:10:29.350
And then I'm going to
do the math myself.

00:10:29.350 --> 00:10:31.480
But you want to have
somebody-- I'm lucky enough

00:10:31.480 --> 00:10:35.030
to have someone that I'm
going to know and trust that's

00:10:35.030 --> 00:10:39.910
going to say, oh, it's not right
next to-- the dump's like two

00:10:39.910 --> 00:10:40.710
miles away.

00:10:40.710 --> 00:10:42.610
And the wind blows right by it.

00:10:42.610 --> 00:10:44.187
JORDAN THIBODEAU: Exactly.

00:10:44.187 --> 00:10:46.020
One issue that we deal
with here in Bay Area

00:10:46.020 --> 00:10:49.420
is, because the cost
of housing is so high,

00:10:49.420 --> 00:10:51.350
that it's really hard
to find good real estate

00:10:51.350 --> 00:10:54.214
investments here.

00:10:54.214 --> 00:10:55.630
For Googlers just
starting out who

00:10:55.630 --> 00:10:58.059
don't have a lot of capital,
are there certain areas

00:10:58.059 --> 00:11:00.600
that you would suggest that we
take a look at for real estate

00:11:00.600 --> 00:11:02.460
investing?

00:11:02.460 --> 00:11:08.140
GINO BLEFARI: Again, I would
say it's all personal to you.

00:11:08.140 --> 00:11:10.350
I had that rule, that one hour.

00:11:10.350 --> 00:11:11.990
I wanted to get one
within one hour.

00:11:11.990 --> 00:11:13.970
So a couple of the
first things I bought

00:11:13.970 --> 00:11:16.050
was down in Morgan Hill.

00:11:16.050 --> 00:11:19.440
I bought a place down in--
I remember like in 1987, I

00:11:19.440 --> 00:11:21.709
bought a brand new
house that Dividend

00:11:21.709 --> 00:11:23.250
was building in
Morgan Hill because I

00:11:23.250 --> 00:11:25.050
could drive to it in an hour.

00:11:25.050 --> 00:11:28.900
And it was certainly
easier to afford.

00:11:28.900 --> 00:11:30.130
JORDAN THIBODEAU: Yeah.

00:11:30.130 --> 00:11:35.390
GINO BLEFARI: Right now, you
have this crazy opportunity,

00:11:35.390 --> 00:11:37.940
and I know lots of the Google
people are millennials.

00:11:37.940 --> 00:11:38.560
You're young.

00:11:38.560 --> 00:11:40.059
But you've got the
crazy opportunity

00:11:40.059 --> 00:11:45.450
of interest rates being really,
really historically low.

00:11:45.450 --> 00:11:51.530
So if I didn't have a house
right now, I'd buy one.

00:11:51.530 --> 00:11:54.500
I wouldn't try to wait for is
the market going to change?

00:11:54.500 --> 00:11:58.050
Actually, the market's actually,
right here in Silicon Valley,

00:11:58.050 --> 00:11:59.990
even though there's
almost no inventory,

00:11:59.990 --> 00:12:01.770
has actually slowed
a bit right now.

00:12:01.770 --> 00:12:04.610
It's starting to
slow a bit right now.

00:12:04.610 --> 00:12:06.780
But let me tell
you the reason why,

00:12:06.780 --> 00:12:09.480
and you almost never will
hear this from anyone.

00:12:09.480 --> 00:12:13.190
In fact, I think a student
one time at De Anza

00:12:13.190 --> 00:12:14.320
asked this question.

00:12:14.320 --> 00:12:16.780
And I went back, and
I did the math on it.

00:12:16.780 --> 00:12:17.600
I say, oh my gosh.

00:12:17.600 --> 00:12:20.440
I wonder why no one's
ever heard of this.

00:12:20.440 --> 00:12:25.220
But let's just pretend
interest rates are 4%.

00:12:25.220 --> 00:12:26.720
Interest rates are 4%.

00:12:26.720 --> 00:12:30.740
And let's just pretend that
interest rates move to 6%.

00:12:30.740 --> 00:12:34.430
Now, in the old days-- in
1989, I paid four points

00:12:34.430 --> 00:12:37.750
to get 10 and an eighth.

00:12:37.750 --> 00:12:39.284
That's just perspective for you.

00:12:39.284 --> 00:12:40.700
But everything
else, it was coming

00:12:40.700 --> 00:12:44.330
down from like 14% and 13%
and right on down there.

00:12:44.330 --> 00:12:46.380
But here's an interesting piece.

00:12:46.380 --> 00:12:50.500
When you make your payment
on a 30-year fixed rate

00:12:50.500 --> 00:12:57.620
loan amortized over 30 years
at 4%, 30% of that payment

00:12:57.620 --> 00:13:00.070
goes toward paying down
your principal of your loan,

00:13:00.070 --> 00:13:01.350
reducing your principal.

00:13:01.350 --> 00:13:06.770
When it moves to
6%, only 17% goes.

00:13:06.770 --> 00:13:11.020
So if you do the math, you
almost have a 13% to 14%.

00:13:11.020 --> 00:13:13.750
It's almost like appreciation
because appreciation's

00:13:13.750 --> 00:13:15.390
gaining equity.

00:13:15.390 --> 00:13:18.920
When you pay off your mortgage,
you're gaining equity.

00:13:18.920 --> 00:13:20.990
And rates are even lower.

00:13:20.990 --> 00:13:23.770
I used 4% and 6% just
because it was kind of easy.

00:13:23.770 --> 00:13:27.120
But it's even better.

00:13:27.120 --> 00:13:33.330
If you're going to buy property,
especially your own house,

00:13:33.330 --> 00:13:37.160
man, that interest rate
is a huge, huge factor.

00:13:37.160 --> 00:13:38.740
And it's totally in our favor.

00:13:38.740 --> 00:13:41.660
Because it's as low as
we've ever seen them.

00:13:41.660 --> 00:13:43.700
And I don't know
what they will do,

00:13:43.700 --> 00:13:46.082
but my guess is they will go up.

00:13:46.082 --> 00:13:47.040
JORDAN THIBODEAU: Fair.

00:13:47.040 --> 00:13:49.330
Now regarding
international markets,

00:13:49.330 --> 00:13:51.030
are there any
international markets

00:13:51.030 --> 00:13:54.350
that you have seen that looks
like a potential good areas

00:13:54.350 --> 00:13:57.260
for real estate investing?

00:13:57.260 --> 00:13:59.620
GINO BLEFARI: Yeah,
you know, international

00:13:59.620 --> 00:14:03.870
is kind of a little
bit more risky.

00:14:03.870 --> 00:14:08.830
