00:14:12.890 --> 00:14:15.890
So I would go to the
ones that traditionally

00:14:15.890 --> 00:14:23.850
have been pretty good
markets like Mexico, Canada.

00:14:23.850 --> 00:14:25.920
Here's the other
thing too though.

00:14:25.920 --> 00:14:28.530
You can get to Cabo San
Lucas in-- how long would it

00:14:28.530 --> 00:14:29.280
take to fly there?

00:14:29.280 --> 00:14:30.940
Deidre, do you know how
long it would takes?

00:14:30.940 --> 00:14:31.160
SPEAKER: 2 and 1/2 hours.

00:14:31.160 --> 00:14:32.570
GINO BLEFARI: 2 and
1/2 hours, right?

00:14:32.570 --> 00:14:34.361
Now you're buying
something over in Europe,

00:14:34.361 --> 00:14:37.610
it's what, 10 and 1/2 hours?

00:14:37.610 --> 00:14:43.636
So I would look to some
of those areas like that.

00:14:43.636 --> 00:14:46.260
JORDAN THIBODEAU: What are your
thoughts on the general housing

00:14:46.260 --> 00:14:47.700
market outside
the United States?

00:14:47.700 --> 00:14:50.158
People are always asking me,
do you think we're in a bubble

00:14:50.158 --> 00:14:51.550
right now?

00:14:51.550 --> 00:14:54.002
Is there more legs in this
economy to keep on going?

00:14:54.002 --> 00:14:54.960
What are your thoughts?

00:14:54.960 --> 00:14:56.710
GINO BLEFARI: Yeah, I
know, that question,

00:14:56.710 --> 00:14:58.390
it's one of those things.

00:14:58.390 --> 00:15:01.510
Before I answer that, I'll
tell you a quick little story.

00:15:01.510 --> 00:15:07.750
In 2004, because Silicon
Valley was going really well,

00:15:07.750 --> 00:15:12.020
I was on "Kudlow &amp;
Cramer," the CNBC.

00:15:12.020 --> 00:15:14.522
And the whole big thing
was, is it a bubble?

00:15:14.522 --> 00:15:15.730
Is the bubble going to burst?

00:15:15.730 --> 00:15:17.630
Or it's a soft landing.

00:15:17.630 --> 00:15:20.350
And, you know, I had
really, really no idea.

00:15:20.350 --> 00:15:23.380
But everybody at that
time, except a few guys

00:15:23.380 --> 00:15:25.830
that had figured it out,
thought we were going

00:15:25.830 --> 00:15:30.290
to be in for a soft landing.

00:15:30.290 --> 00:15:35.490
Before I say, how many of you
think that we're in a bubble?

00:15:35.490 --> 00:15:38.330
So maybe a third of you.

00:15:38.330 --> 00:15:43.420
And then the 2/3 say that
we're not in a bubble.

00:15:43.420 --> 00:15:47.000
If I had to guess, and
it would only be a guess,

00:15:47.000 --> 00:15:49.090
I would say we're
not in a bubble.

00:15:49.090 --> 00:15:53.360
And here's why I back that up.

00:15:53.360 --> 00:15:58.260
When we had the
bubble in like 2000,

00:15:58.260 --> 00:16:00.940
but I guess the bubble
burst, what, in about 2007?

00:16:00.940 --> 00:16:02.200
OK, let's say bubbles burst.

00:16:02.200 --> 00:16:06.730
There was a thing called
a negatively amortized

00:16:06.730 --> 00:16:10.670
adjustable rate
subprime mortgage.

00:16:10.670 --> 00:16:14.100
And what that was was a
mortgage that when you start out

00:16:14.100 --> 00:16:15.600
at a very, very low rate.

00:16:15.600 --> 00:16:17.510
And that's what your rate was.

00:16:17.510 --> 00:16:20.320
Negatively amortization
means really payment's

00:16:20.320 --> 00:16:21.380
supposed to be up here.

00:16:21.380 --> 00:16:23.190
But I'm only making
the payment down here.

00:16:23.190 --> 00:16:24.120
And what I'm going to
do with the payment

00:16:24.120 --> 00:16:25.920
that you were supposed to
make up here, that difference,

00:16:25.920 --> 00:16:28.336
I'm going to add that on to
the back end of your mortgage.

00:16:28.336 --> 00:16:33.000
Now, that only works if
property is totally, totally,

00:16:33.000 --> 00:16:35.450
totally appreciating.

00:16:35.450 --> 00:16:39.390
The next piece to
that was back then--

00:16:39.390 --> 00:16:42.400
and now those loans
are pretty much gone.

00:16:42.400 --> 00:16:44.630
There's government
regulations that you

00:16:44.630 --> 00:16:46.210
can't do that type of a loan.

00:16:46.210 --> 00:16:48.280
The other thing--
there were loans where

00:16:48.280 --> 00:16:49.940
you wouldn't verify anything.

00:16:49.940 --> 00:16:52.930
We almost called them liar
loans, like as a joke.

00:16:52.930 --> 00:16:57.420
It's a liar loan because there
was no verification of anything

00:16:57.420 --> 00:17:00.060
that was put down on
the loan application.

00:17:00.060 --> 00:17:02.830
So all sorts of people
got loans that they never

00:17:02.830 --> 00:17:04.050
should have gotten.

00:17:04.050 --> 00:17:05.460
And that doesn't happen.

00:17:05.460 --> 00:17:08.430
So the only way that those
people that got all those loans

00:17:08.430 --> 00:17:11.770
could even survive was with
the market accelerating

00:17:11.770 --> 00:17:13.819
at a crazy, crazy space.

00:17:13.819 --> 00:17:17.190
And if my balloon
payment came in,

00:17:17.190 --> 00:17:19.450
it was OK, because I
just refinanced out of it

00:17:19.450 --> 00:17:22.410
and got another
adjustable rate mortgage.

00:17:22.410 --> 00:17:24.660
Those days are gone.

00:17:24.660 --> 00:17:28.000
We don't have those
specific days now anymore

00:17:28.000 --> 00:17:29.050
because of that.

00:17:29.050 --> 00:17:31.080
So to that, I would
say maybe we don't

00:17:31.080 --> 00:17:34.920
have a big bubble
where it's going

00:17:34.920 --> 00:17:37.740
to burst like it did in 2007.

00:17:37.740 --> 00:17:41.650
How many of you saw the
movie "The Big Short"?

00:17:41.650 --> 00:17:42.660
Almost all of you, yeah.

00:17:42.660 --> 00:17:44.430
That was a pretty
darn good movie.

00:17:44.430 --> 00:17:45.890
How many of you
have read the book?

00:17:45.890 --> 00:17:47.770
It was Michael Lewis's
book, "The Big Short."

00:17:47.770 --> 00:17:48.410
OK.

00:17:48.410 --> 00:17:51.300
It really talked about
the negatively amortized

00:17:51.300 --> 00:17:53.096
adjustable rate
subprime mortgage,

00:17:53.096 --> 00:17:54.762
and it also talked
about it in the book.

00:18:00.560 --> 00:18:04.720
He was talking to the
lady in the club, right?

00:18:04.720 --> 00:18:08.090
And she owned like-- he goes,
well, how about your condo?

00:18:08.090 --> 00:18:10.680
How you doing on your--
well, I own six houses.

00:18:10.680 --> 00:18:12.800
I mean, people just
owned and owned

00:18:12.800 --> 00:18:15.270
and owned because
anybody could get a loan.

00:18:15.270 --> 00:18:16.840
And we don't have that anymore.

00:18:16.840 --> 00:18:17.790
It's a lot harder.

00:18:17.790 --> 00:18:20.890
So I'd say government
regulations

00:18:20.890 --> 00:18:25.050
have played a role in that.

00:18:25.050 --> 00:18:28.370
JORDAN THIBODEAU: Yeah, so today
