But they also have
about 26 companies.

00:21:58.350 --> 00:22:00.570
Like when you see
an Intero sign now,

00:22:00.570 --> 00:22:05.170
you'll see it say "Intero, a
Berkshire Hathaway affiliate."

00:22:05.170 --> 00:22:07.100
So they're a big company.

00:22:07.100 --> 00:22:12.980
And the consumer on every
survey going back to 1995

00:22:12.980 --> 00:22:15.460
has always said they
want a one-stop shop.

00:22:15.460 --> 00:22:18.880
So what we try to do as
a real estate company

00:22:18.880 --> 00:22:23.720
is provide mortgage, title,
homeowners insurance,

00:22:23.720 --> 00:22:26.290
personal insurance.

00:22:26.290 --> 00:22:29.080
It's a whole gamut
of the whole thing.

00:22:29.080 --> 00:22:31.829
I think you were
referring to RESPA.

00:22:31.829 --> 00:22:33.870
Is everybody familiar with
RESPA, the Real Estate

00:22:33.870 --> 00:22:35.030
Procedures Act?

00:22:35.030 --> 00:22:40.570
And that's where no one can
receive anything of value

00:22:40.570 --> 00:22:43.740
on directing a
settlement service.

00:22:43.740 --> 00:22:45.910
However, when
you're a big company

00:22:45.910 --> 00:22:51.120
and you own the whole thing,
and a manager's an employee,

00:22:51.120 --> 00:22:55.520
the manager could be
incentivized to increase

00:22:55.520 --> 00:22:58.570
the capture rate on mortgage.

00:22:58.570 --> 00:23:01.090
A realtor now is an
independent contractor.

00:23:01.090 --> 00:23:04.980
They could not receive
anything of value

00:23:04.980 --> 00:23:08.270
for directing business to a
settlement service company.

00:23:08.270 --> 00:23:10.700
I will tell you this.

00:23:10.700 --> 00:23:13.750
The companies-- and many
big companies have them.

00:23:13.750 --> 00:23:19.670
The ones that do, you're better
off almost 100% of the time

00:23:19.670 --> 00:23:23.310
using a company that
has all those services

00:23:23.310 --> 00:23:29.540
because those providers are
held to a higher standard,

00:23:29.540 --> 00:23:30.830
even by the regulators.

00:23:30.830 --> 00:23:33.840
If you get a 0% for
a mortgage, you'd

00:23:33.840 --> 00:23:37.490
have a $0 on that
closing statement.

00:23:37.490 --> 00:23:41.790
It can be off $0 if
it's the own company.

00:23:41.790 --> 00:23:45.500
If it's an outside company,
it can be off as much as 10%

00:23:45.500 --> 00:23:47.910
and still fall under
the regulation.

00:23:47.910 --> 00:23:52.930
So the other thing too is
there's a whole reputation

00:23:52.930 --> 00:23:53.980
piece.

00:23:53.980 --> 00:23:55.531
It's all based on service.

00:23:55.531 --> 00:23:57.530
You've got to give great,
great service in order

00:23:57.530 --> 00:23:58.988
to get the business,
whether you're

00:23:58.988 --> 00:24:00.697
the title, whether
the mortgage provider,

00:24:00.697 --> 00:24:03.154
whether you're the insurance
provider and things like that.

00:24:03.154 --> 00:24:05.070
But when it's all right
in the same family,

00:24:05.070 --> 00:24:06.870
it's scrutinized a lot closer.

00:24:06.870 --> 00:24:08.990
JORDAN THIBODEAU: Gotcha.

00:24:08.990 --> 00:24:11.910
Can you share your views on
the title insurance market?

00:24:11.910 --> 00:24:15.490
"The New York Times" has some
unfavorable words regarding it.

00:24:15.490 --> 00:24:18.420
And they think it's kind of--
the field is an oligopoly.

00:24:18.420 --> 00:24:20.770
GINO BLEFARI: Yeah, title adds.

00:24:20.770 --> 00:24:25.500
I always kind of
almost smile when

00:24:25.500 --> 00:24:26.780
it comes to title insurance.

00:24:26.780 --> 00:24:31.240
But let me just explain
what title insurance is.

00:24:31.240 --> 00:24:33.910
Title insurance is
a one time-- most

00:24:33.910 --> 00:24:35.750
insurance you pay every year.

00:24:35.750 --> 00:24:37.250
You renew your
insurance every year.

00:24:37.250 --> 00:24:39.660
Title insurance is
a one time where

00:24:39.660 --> 00:24:44.590
they're assuring that the title
is exactly what you thought it

00:24:44.590 --> 00:24:45.840
was when you bought the house.

